<section class="hero">
  <div>
    <p class="eyebrow">TypeScript roots, modern language ergonomics</p>
    <h1>Learn MyLang interactively.</h1>
    <p class="lead">MyLang keeps the familiar JavaScript and TypeScript ecosystem while adding concise declarations, value classes, null-aware access, string templates, trailing lambdas, and sync-style asynchronous code.</p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button" href="#playground">Try the editor</a>
      <a class="button secondary" href="/syntax/">Open syntax reference</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="code-panel" aria-label="MyLang code sample">
    <div class="panel-title">hello.my</div>
<pre><code>class User(val name: string, val score: int)

sync fun loadMessage(user: User): string {
  let bonus = fetchBonus(user.name)
  return $"Hello {user.name}, score: {user.score + bonus}"
}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="syntax" class="section alt">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">Syntax tour</p>
    <h2>Readable syntax for application code.</h2>
    <p class="lead">The full supported syntax reference now lives on its own page and is rendered directly from the canonical documentation file.</p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button secondary" href="/syntax/">Read the full syntax guide</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Concise declarations</h3>
      <p>Use <code>fun</code> or <code>function</code>, <code>val</code> for read-only values, and primary-constructor class members.</p>
<pre><code>class Point(val x: number, val y: number)
fun length(p: Point): number { return p.x + p.y }</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Null-aware access</h3>
      <p>Optional chaining, non-null assertions, and type analysis help make nullable flows explicit.</p>
<pre><code>let city = user.address?.city ?? "Unknown"
let name = maybeUser!.name</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Sync async style</h3>
      <p><code>sync</code> functions automatically await produced promises, while <code>go</code> keeps a promise for fire-and-forget or manual orchestration.</p>
<pre><code>sync fun main(): int {
  let value = fetchValue()
  return value + 1
}</code></pre>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="examples" class="section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>
    <h2>Patterns that teach the language.</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Trailing lambdas</h3>
<pre><code>items.map { item ->
  return item.name
}</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Extension members</h3>
<pre><code>extension string {
  fun shout(): string { return this.toUpperCase() }
}</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Namespaces</h3>
<pre><code>namespace Tools {
  export const version = 1
}</code></pre>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

